Dreaming of the Winter Wonderland❄️

Interesting thing. Last year on the New Year's Eve my husband came down with a fever and the celebration was canceled. He went to bed at midnight and I was drinking wine alone on the floor. I thought to myself "I hope the 2022 won't be the same as it started". Well... what an irony. It was exactly as it started. It was one of the shittiest years. So honestly. I'm not excited about 2023.

As an artist I often question myself why I do what I do. Among other reasons like craving for beauty and whimsy, love for fantasy and fairy tales, I think one of the reasons is escapism to other reality. The reality that is more magical, beautiful and kind. Where there's no war, despair and disappointment.

Sorry for maybe such a gloomy post. But I find importance and value in all human emotions. Including sadness.

I truly hope the next year will be better.

Happy Holiday season!❄️🎄

Winter Wonderland❄️ Little compilation of snowy frosty images dedicated to one of my favorite times of the year☃️

Winter is almost over. Here in New York it's been the warmest and the least snowy winter in the last 50 years. This year there was literally NO measurable snow at all. It sprinkled only a couple of times and melted immediately. As climate change progresses I guess white winters will become less and less common.

I love winter and I love snow❄️ There's something magical about it. I miss it so much. Growing up as a kid in central Ukraine I remember it very well. Glittering snow in the street lights, crunching sounds when you walk on it, frost curls and swirls on the window glass, catching snowflakes with your mittens and admire their beauty, frostnips on your cheeks, sleigh rides, snowmen making. But even in Ukraine it is nothing like it used to be for the last 20 years.

Happy Earth Day! 🌎 "2.5 Seconds" is a climate change awareness project. It is a series of photographs that highlight the environmental crisis through metaphors and symbolism. Each photograph illustrates and represents a specific environmental issue using allegorical figures and subjects, props, costumes and natural landscapes. In total, I illustrated 8 different environmental issues and created 13 artworks. We have Global Warming, Sea Level Rise, Extreme weather, Plastic pollution, Deforestation, Pollution, Glacier melt, and Greenhouse Gases.

Nesting 🕊

Model @melanierosebud
Hair @jessefox21hair

Earlier this year Jesse approached me with a desire to create something together and offered to style the hair for the shoot. I was thrilled and immediately agreed because it had been far too long since I last did any creative project, and I was in a creative slump. The idea of incorporating a bird's nest into the hair came to me instantly. I’ve had this idea for a while but was uncertain about how to bring it to life. I previously worked with Melanie and offered her to be our model. We traveled to Jesse's studio in New Jersey and captured the photos in his backyard during the sunset in early spring. The timing was perfect as I specifically wanted bare branches in the backdrop for this concept. Thank you Jesse and Melanie. You did an amazing job, and this photoshoot wouldn't have been possible without you.

It's ok to change your mind about photography.

I shot this image in 2018 when traveling through the Faroe Islands. Saksun is a teeny-tiny village with population of only 8 people and is located on the North of Faroe islands. There's this spot with an incredible view on the lagoon and of course these magical houses with grass on the rooftops. I just had to shoot there. I imagined myself as a construction worker who covers these rooftops with grass.

When I posted the image it received positive feedback and people seemed to really like it. However, it always bothered me. Something was off. And it was my outfit and the sloppy roll of grass on the ground. I love the idea but it really lacked some workwear. The sweater and jeans bothered me because they didn't complete the story I had in mind. So I decided to change it.

Going back and reshooting wasn't an option. But I had the power of Photoshop. I bought work overalls, extra rolls of moss, waited for the optimal weather conditions and right time of the day and went to a local park in Brooklyn. I carefully chose spot and ange to replicate the scene and make it as close to the original as possible. We took additional shots of me wearing overalls and the roll of moss unraveled on the ground.

Swipe left to see the image I initially posted and the additional shots we took for the new composite.

I think it looks so much better and completes the story. What do you think? Was it worth the effort?

Made with @photoshop @Lightroom @wacom @nikonusa @benqnorthamerica

Over the last couple of months, I’ve been playing with the new Generative Fill in Photoshop. I have a strong opinion about AI, but I realize it’s becoming a part of our reality and I should learn more about it.

This new tool is impressive and mind-blowing. I’m astonished at how well and precisely it analyzes the light and accurately recreates shadows and highlights. It works the best with extending frames and adding simple out-of-focus elements such as trees, flowers, etc. It's excellent for simple tasks and saves a lot of time compared to manual methods. Something like sourcing stock images, manipulating and stealing pieces from other photos would normally take me hours, Generative Fill now does it in seconds.

I mostly played with it in my lifestyle and travel photos, BTS images. I can't fully incorporate it into my work yet. For now, it only works for small image sizes suitable for Instagram. If you have bigger size files and you zoom in you will see that generated areas are pixelated, as if they were a scaled low-resolution image, and have a lot of artifacts. Also, it doesn’t do well with complicated composites. It gave me terrible results with swapping clothes, backgrounds, and adding more detailed elements.

Despite this, I decided to give it a try and played with another old artwork of mine. To be honest I’ve never been a big fan of how this image came out. I decided to spice it up a bit and add more clouds as if I was floating in the sky. I played around with different Generative Fill options and fixed artifacts. I’m pretty happy with the results and I can't wait when it is able to produce high-resolution images.

I must admit, as a creator I’m loving it. I appreciate the fact that Generative Fill is powered by Adobe Firefly, a model trained on stock imagery, openly licensed work, and public domain content. To me, this is exactly how a tool powered by AI should be: an extension and improvement to your process that doesn’t replace you or your creative processes entirely. But as a professional retoucher and educator, I’m still very concerned about where and how my career will go.

Swipe left to see the original artwork from 2015 and a speed edit video👉🏻
Using Photoshop Generative Fill to reimagine one of my old photos 🌙
My only 10/10 photos. What do you think?

We used to look up at the sky and wonder at our place in the stars✨️

The enchanting wonders of space and the cosmos inspire me and captivate my imagination. The dance of stars, the vastness of galaxies, and the mysteries of space and time fill me with awe and curiosity. This fascination with the universe often fuels my creativity and reminds me of the limitless potential that exists beyond our world. The cosmos serves as a metaphor for wandering, exploration of new horizons and embracing the beauty of the unknown✨️🌙

Dear deer 🤍✨️ Here's the first portrait from the deer small series I photographed back in April! So there's more to come:) I wanted this series to be whimsical but also soft and feminine. That's why I wanted to photograph it during the cherry blooming season and waited for spring. I shot it with my old manual Helios-40 lens for that dreamy effect, soft focus and signature swirly bokeh.

I used antlers and deer ears I purchased from Etsy. The wig I got from Amazon and it's the one I used for Mermaid images. Truly a multifunctional one:) I edited the hairline to make it as realistic as possible. I decided to give Generative Fill a try for that. I selected the hairline and just typed in "natural hairline". And boom! Worked like magic.

Thank you girls @gabby_lana
& @charkova_irina for making this magic happen!

That's because I missed the focus on the whole set🫠 But I really liked the pose and angle so I decided to go with it anyway.
